</taxonomicName>
, female from Australia (Tarwin Lower), ventral habitus.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1487,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">
<bibRefCitation author="Lacordaire, J. T." box="[199,402,1487,1514]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" refId="ref11483" refString="Lacordaire, J. T. (1868) Histoire Naturelle des Insectes. Genera des Coleopteres, ou expose methodique et critique de tous les genres proposes jusqu'ici dans cet ordre d'insectes. Vol. 8. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, 552 pp." type="book" year="1868">Lacordaire (1868)</bibRefCitation>
separated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[521,638,1487,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[521,638,1487,1513]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[705,842,1487,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[705,842,1487,1513]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his key: “b. Antennae filiform or setaceous,” leading to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[222,339,1523,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[222,339,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; “bb. Antennae fusiform; metatibiae denticulate,” leading to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[1018,1155,1523,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1018,1155,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the difference in the antennal shape does not allow separating these genera, even considering only the species included by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lacordaire, J. T." pageId="5" pageNumber="358" refId="ref11483" refString="Lacordaire, J. T. (1868) Histoire Naturelle des Insectes. Genera des Coleopteres, ou expose methodique et critique de tous les genres proposes jusqu'ici dans cet ordre d'insectes. Vol. 8. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, 552 pp." type="book" year="1868">Lacordaire (1868)</bibRefCitation>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[330,467,1595,1621]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[330,467,1595,1621]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For example, the antennae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pascoe, 1866" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1866" box="[821,1081,1595,1622]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[821,922,1596,1621]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">M. acuta</emphasis>
Pascoe, 1866
</taxonomicName>
do not differ from those in the 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,1632,1658]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[321,438,1631,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[321,438,1631,1657]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, at least part of this misconception was made by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pascoe, F. P." box="[1063,1224,1631,1658]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" pagination="236 - 266" refId="ref12259" refString="Pascoe, F. P. (1858) On new genera and species of longicorn Coleoptera. Part III. The Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, Series 2, 4, 236 - 266. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1858. tb 01823. x" type="journal article" year="1858">Pascoe (1858)</bibRefCitation>
, who described the antennae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pascoe, 1858" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[285,575,1667,1694]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[285,422,1667,1693]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pascoe, F. P." box="[428,575,1667,1694]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" pagination="236 - 266" refId="ref12259" refString="Pascoe, F. P. (1858) On new genera and species of longicorn Coleoptera. Part III. The Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, Series 2, 4, 236 - 266. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1858. tb 01823. x" type="journal article" year="1858">Pascoe, 1858</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as “short, claviform, the six or seven last joints dilated,” and had included 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hope, 1831)" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">M. indica</emphasis>
(Hope, 1831)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(White, 1855)" baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[435,743,1703,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis box="[435,577,1704,1729]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
(White, 1855)
</taxonomicName>
in the genus; these two species have all antennomeres nearly cylindrical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1487,2018]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">
Nearly all species 
<taxonomicName authority="(Merionoeda)" box="[416,718,1775,1802]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Merionoeda">
<emphasis box="[416,553,1775,1801]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[572,709,1775,1801]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
have distinct spicules on the metatibiae (according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Pascoe, F. P." pageId="5" pageNumber="358" pagination="236 - 266" refId="ref12259" refString="Pascoe, F. P. (1858) On new genera and species of longicorn Coleoptera. Part III. The Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, Series 2, 4, 236 - 266. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1858. tb 01823. x" type="journal article" year="1858">Pascoe (1858)</bibRefCitation>
, they are “serrated and spurred”), which are absent in the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[1005,1122,1811,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1005,1122,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, as there are species lacking the spicules on the metatibiae (
<emphasis box="[662,702,1848,1873]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">e.g.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Yokoi &amp; Niisato, 2012" authorityName="Yokoi &amp; Niisato" authorityYear="2012" box="[713,1106,1847,1874]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glabra">
<emphasis box="[713,829,1847,1873]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">M. glabra</emphasis>
Yokoi &amp; Niisato, 2012
</taxonomicName>
), the differentiation between 
<taxonomicName authority="(Merionoeda)" box="[151,451,1883,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Merionoeda">
<emphasis box="[151,288,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[305,442,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[507,624,1883,1909]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[507,624,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on this feature is problematic. The sixth ventrite (sternite VIII) in the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[311,428,1919,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[311,428,1919,1945]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly exposed at the abdominal apex. However, it is also distinctly exposed at least in 
<taxonomicName authority="Adlbauer, 1994" authorityName="Adlbauer" authorityYear="1994" box="[182,897,1955,1982]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="africana" subGenus="Merionoeda" subSpecies="aethiopica">
<emphasis box="[182,319,1955,1981]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[336,473,1955,1981]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[491,713,1955,1982]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">africana aethiopica</emphasis>
Adlbauer, 1994
</taxonomicName>
, the only species examined by us. Therefore, it is another feature that does not help in separating 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[718,835,1991,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[718,835,1991,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Merionoeda)" box="[905,1207,1991,2018]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Merionoeda">
<emphasis box="[905,1042,1991,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1059,1196,1991,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Merionoeda</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
. For the time being, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[151,268,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,268,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is maintained as a distinct genus, until a greater number of species of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Merionoeda)" box="[1090,1392,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Merionoeda">
<emphasis box="[1090,1227,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1246,1383,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
are studied. Moreover, it seems evident to us that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[663,800,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[663,800,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(including the three subgenera) should be excluded from 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1848" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1848" box="[151,431,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Stenopterini">Stenopterini Gistel, 1848</taxonomicName>
and included in 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins &amp; Galileo, 2003" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2003" box="[615,1023,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Oxycoleini">
Oxycoleini 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[746,1023,223,249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" refId="ref11576" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (2003) Tribo Oxycoleini. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-americanos (Coleoptera) Taxonomia. Vol. 6. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 51 - 63." type="book" year="2003">Martins &amp; Galileo, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the abdominal setation on the ventrites 2 and 3 of the females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[199,316,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,316,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1922" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1922" box="[465,932,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Macromolorchus">
<emphasis box="[465,602,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[618,809,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Macromolorchus</emphasis>
) Pic, 1922
</taxonomicName>
especially by the absence of the tuft of setae on the metatibiae (present in nearly all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[718,855,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[718,855,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[872,1063,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Macromolorchus</emphasis>
)), and by the absence of a dense tuft of long setae on the ventral surface of the metafemoral club (present in all species of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Macromolorchus">
<emphasis box="[1158,1295,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Macromolorchus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
, although, sometimes, not dense). Finally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[718,835,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[718,835,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Pascoe, 1869" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1869" box="[984,1401,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ocytasia">
<emphasis box="[984,1121,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1137,1237,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Ocytasia</emphasis>
) Pascoe, 1869
</taxonomicName>
by the mesotarsomeres of the males without modifications (mesotarsomeres I and II distinctly projected on the outer side in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1858" box="[230,367,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[230,367,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[383,483,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Ocytasia</emphasis>
)), and meso- and metatarsi with similar appearance (strongly different in 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ocytasia">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Merionoeda</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[161,261,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Ocytasia</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
, in which the mesotarsi are much wider than the metatarsi).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">
Even with the transference of one species from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[748,865,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[748,865,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1872" box="[904,1048,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tethlimmena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[904,1048,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Tethlimmena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and three to 
<taxonomicName authority="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva, 2021" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2021" box="[1209,1317,547,572]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Wappesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1209,1317,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Wappesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1326,1432,547,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the genus still includes two groups of species: 1. Elytra strongly narrowed toward apex, which is at least somewhat acute; 2. Elytra not strongly narrowed toward apex, which is rounded. In the group of species with rounded apex, the humeral carina may be complete, from base to apex, as in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Zajciw, 1964)" baseAuthorityName="Zajciw" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[849,1220,655,682]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Merionoeda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carinatipennis">
<emphasis box="[849,1046,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">O. carinatipennis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zajciw, D." box="[1060,1212,655,682]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" pagination="247 - 256" refId="ref12643" refString="Zajciw, D. (1964) Revisao das especies brasileiras do genero Merionoeda Pascoe (Col., Cerambycidae). Studia Entomologica, 7 (1 - 4), 247 - 256." type="journal article" year="1964">Zajciw, 1964</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, or present only on posterior half or apically or even absent as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Julio, 1997" authorityName="Julio" authorityYear="1997" box="[656,889,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laetus">
<emphasis box="[656,756,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">O. laetus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Julio, C. E. A." box="[762,889,691,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref11374" refString="Julio, C. E. A. (1997) Descricoes, sinonimia, novo status, novas combinacoes e chave para as especies brasileiras de Oxycoleus Lacordaire, 1869 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Cerambycinae, Molorchini). Boletim do Museu Nacional, Zoologia, 381, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1997">Júlio, 1997</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It is possible that there are species of two genera still included in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1868" box="[336,453,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,453,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">Oxycoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: one with acute elytral apex; another with rounded elytral apex. However, the position of the humeral carina in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2006" box="[429,551,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Oxycoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[429,551,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="359">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
